<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="585" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1909,2008]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,151,537]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="585" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,373,1909,1935]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Description. Male.</emphasis>
Body compact, dorso-ventrally flattened, elongate (
<figureCitation box="[965,1091,1909,1935]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-183@2.[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Damzenium rivnense gen. et sp. nov. A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Figs 1A–F</figureCitation>
). Head transverse, slightly exposed from pronotum. Eyes moderately large, spherical. Antenna 11-segmented, relatively short, robust, antennomeres only slightly flattened and feebly dentate; pedicel (antennomere 2) slightly longer than wide, ca 2.5 times shorter than antennomere 3, antennomere 3 subequal in length to antennomere 4 and subsequent antennomeres; pubescence on antennomeres 3–11 short and decumbent (
<figureCitation box="[795,919,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-183@2.[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Damzenium rivnense gen. et sp. nov. A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Figs 1A, F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">
Pronotum transverse, almost straight anteriorly, with complete narrow median and somewhat zig-zagged transverse lateral carinae; posterior angles acute (
<figureCitation box="[644,772,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-183@2.[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Damzenium rivnense gen. et sp. nov. A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Figs 1A–C</figureCitation>
). Scutellum triangular, rounded at apex (
<figureCitation box="[1222,1349,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-183@2.[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Damzenium rivnense gen. et sp. nov. A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Figs 1A–C</figureCitation>
). Elytra elongate, flattened, with three distinct costae on the dorsal surface, with double rows of cells in their interstices; humeral elytral costa (costa 3) stout in all its length, costa 1 weakened in distal fourth; last elytral interstice (lateriad of humeral costa) wide, ca. 2 times wider than interstices 1–3, with three to four unclear rows of elytral cells, i.e., longitudinal costa 4 is weak and partly indistinct; elytral pubescence relatively short and decumbent (
<figureCitation box="[1298,1424,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-183@2.[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Damzenium rivnense gen. et sp. nov. A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Figs 1A–F</figureCitation>
). Metathoracic wings presumably fully developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,151,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">
Legs relatively short and robust; femurs and tibiae straight, subequal in length, slightly widening distally; tarsomeres 2–4 slightly widened; claws simple (
<figureCitation box="[660,749,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-183@2.[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Damzenium rivnense gen. et sp. nov. A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="585" startId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" targetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1809,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,1809,1834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Kazantsev &amp; Bocak, 2022" authorityName="Kazantsev &amp; Bocak" authorityYear="2022" box="[283,498,1810,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Damzenium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="585" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rivnense" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[283,498,1810,1833]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Damzenium rivnense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[505,665,1810,1834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[505,665,1810,1834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="585" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1916,2014]" box="[199,859,1916,1942]" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Abdomen with semicircularly incised penultimate ventrite.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="586" pageId="2" pageNumber="585" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1916,2014]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,429]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="586" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1952,1978]" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Kazantsev &amp; Bocak, 2022" authorityName="Kazantsev &amp; Bocak" authorityYear="2022" box="[328,462,1953,1978]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Damzenium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="585" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[328,462,1953,1978]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Damzenium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[469,574,1952,1978]" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[469,574,1952,1978]" pageId="2" pageNumber="585" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
may be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kazantsev" authorityYear="2013" box="[888,1048,1952,1978]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Protolopheros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="585" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[888,1048,1952,1978]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Protolopheros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1940" box="[1102,1312,1952,1978]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pseudaplatopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="585" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1102,1312,1952,1978]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="585">Pseudaplatopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from Baltic amber, by the stout elytral costa 3 (counting from the suture), which is robust in its entire length compared to only basally stout costa 
<quantity box="[425,469,151,177]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kazantsev" authorityYear="2013" box="[477,637,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Protolopheros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[477,637,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Protolopheros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1940" box="[693,903,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pseudaplatopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[693,903,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Pseudaplatopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[920,1011,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1627,1651]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,184,1597]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[151,1436,181,1603]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. A—J. Morphology of the extant Erotinae. A—Eropterus sp., Japan, general appearance, dorsal view; B–D— elytron, humeral part. B—Eropterus sp., Japan; C—Benibotarus spinicoxis (Kiesenwetter), Japan; D—Lopheros sp., Japan. E— G—Pronotum. E—Eropterus trilineatus (Melsheimer), USA, dorsal view; F—Lopheros sp., Japan; G—Benibotarus spinicoxis (Kiesenwetter), Japan. H– J General appearance, dorsal view. H—Helcophorus miniatus Fairmaire, Himalayas; I—Greenarus belokobylskyi Kazantsev, Vietnam; J—Laterialis sanguinea Kazantsev, China. Eocene Erotini. K—Protolopheros hoffeinsorum Kazantsev, Baltic amber (photo from Kazantsev, 2013). Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655708/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Fig. 2K</figureCitation>
), and by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kazantsev &amp; Bocak" authorityYear="2022" box="[1117,1251,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Damzenium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1117,1251,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Damzenium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’s regular elytral reticulation with even rows of round cells in interstices, which differs from the irregular elytral reticulation in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kazantsev" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Protolopheros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Protolopheros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[262,397,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-183@2.[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Damzenium rivnense gen. et sp. nov. A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Figs 1A, 1E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[408,446,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1627,1651]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,184,1597]" captionTargetId="figure-23@4.[151,1436,181,1603]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. A—J. Morphology of the extant Erotinae. A—Eropterus sp., Japan, general appearance, dorsal view; B–D— elytron, humeral part. B—Eropterus sp., Japan; C—Benibotarus spinicoxis (Kiesenwetter), Japan; D—Lopheros sp., Japan. E— G—Pronotum. E—Eropterus trilineatus (Melsheimer), USA, dorsal view; F—Lopheros sp., Japan; G—Benibotarus spinicoxis (Kiesenwetter), Japan. H– J General appearance, dorsal view. H—Helcophorus miniatus Fairmaire, Himalayas; I—Greenarus belokobylskyi Kazantsev, Vietnam; J—Laterialis sanguinea Kazantsev, China. Eocene Erotini. K—Protolopheros hoffeinsorum Kazantsev, Baltic amber (photo from Kazantsev, 2013). Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655708" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655708/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">2K</figureCitation>
). The new genus also differs from all the extant genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1881" box="[1083,1164,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Erotini">Erotini</taxonomicName>
, which are characterized by the equally developed elytral costae. 
<taxonomicName authority="Kazantsev &amp; Bocak, 2022" authorityName="Kazantsev &amp; Bocak" authorityYear="2022" box="[600,734,259,284]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Damzenium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[600,734,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Damzenium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[741,845,259,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[741,845,259,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
has a different arrangement of elytral costae, including the much stouter humeral costa (
<figureCitation box="[555,691,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-183@2.[151,1436,561,1786]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Damzenium rivnense gen. et sp. nov. A—general appearance, dorsal view, B, C—pronotum and humeral part of the elytra, D, E—posterior and humeral part of the right elytron; F—general appearance, lateral view. Scales 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6655706" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6655706/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Figs 1A, 1E</figureCitation>
). Such a robust primary costa 3 has not been known in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1881" box="[1305,1386,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Erotini">Erotini</taxonomicName>
, and therefore, this species cannot be attributed to any extant genus and deserves to be described as a new genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="586" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,367,393]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new genus is named in honour of Mr. J. Damzen (
<collectingRegion box="[942,1027,367,393]" country="Lithuania" name="Vilniaus" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Vilnius</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1038,1150,367,394]" name="Lithuania" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Lithuania</collectingCountry>
), who generously gave us the opportunity to study this remarkable amber specimen. Gender neuter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
